Let's assume there is a conducting sphere where you have a +q charge at the
center of it and you want to find the induced charge of it in the inner
surface(A) and the outer surface(B) of conductor. ^YfIO1w1Q

So the theory here is that the E.F.I,
inside a conducting sphere should be 0.
Therefore to make it zero, a charge equal
in magnitude and opposite in charge has to
be induced in the inside surface ^wmpWha4o

Therefore a -q charge will be induced 
inside the sphere at A. ^DllSFxnd

But what about the outside surface? Well, if the conductor previously had no charge,
(a neutral conductor) then, the same magnitude as the one in inner surface but opposite 
in charge will be induced so that they cancel out and the sphere is kept neutral ^J0QVLhUh

Therefore a +q charge will be induced outside the sphere surface at B ^4a7FOv3T

But in a case where its a charged sphere, then the that pre-existsing charge should be 
equal to the sum of the charges induced in inner and outer surfaces. ^GgvR2JyO
